<figureCitation id="42745F419BFD280F7BFA3192FDB67908" captionStart="Figures 9, 10" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figures 9, 10. 9 Bledius gallicus (Gravenhorst) 9 A habitus, black elytra, L. Borowiec 9 B habitus, red-brown elytra, L. Borowiec 9 C aedeagus, ventral view, VL = ventral lamella M. Schuelke 9 D male sternite VII 10 Carpelimus elongatulus (Erichson) 10 A habitus 10 B aedeagus, ventral view, H. Schillhammer. Scale bars: 1.0 mm (9 A, B; 10 A), 0.2 mm (9 C), 0.2 mm (9 D), 0.25 mm (10 B)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.894.37862.figures9-10" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/362142" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.894.37862.figures9-10">Fig. 9A, B</figureCitation>
. Male sternite VII as in 
<figureCitation id="3335E4E52156674CCB091681E139EF5E" captionStart="Figures 9, 10" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figures 9, 10. 9 Bledius gallicus (Gravenhorst) 9 A habitus, black elytra, L. Borowiec 9 B habitus, red-brown elytra, L. Borowiec 9 C aedeagus, ventral view, VL = ventral lamella M. Schuelke 9 D male sternite VII 10 Carpelimus elongatulus (Erichson) 10 A habitus 10 B aedeagus, ventral view, H. Schillhammer. Scale bars: 1.0 mm (9 A, B; 10 A), 0.2 mm (9 C), 0.2 mm (9 D), 0.25 mm (10 B)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.894.37862.figures9-10" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/362142" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.894.37862.figures9-10">Fig. 9D</figureCitation>
. Aedeagus as in 
<figureCitation id="7392E89FA32F0CEBBAB2DA954532CF57" captionStart="Figures 9, 10" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figures 9, 10. 9 Bledius gallicus (Gravenhorst) 9 A habitus, black elytra, L. Borowiec 9 B habitus, red-brown elytra, L. Borowiec 9 C aedeagus, ventral view, VL = ventral lamella M. Schuelke 9 D male sternite VII 10 Carpelimus elongatulus (Erichson) 10 A habitus 10 B aedeagus, ventral view, H. Schillhammer. Scale bars: 1.0 mm (9 A, B; 10 A), 0.2 mm (9 C), 0.2 mm (9 D), 0.25 mm (10 B)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.894.37862.figures9-10" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/362142" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.894.37862.figures9-10">Fig. 9C</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="E42CC41C1AA6F1673D39EC93A7A78F41" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" type="bionomic notes">
<paragraph id="854445BC148011A260E1A786FE1F436E" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Bionomic notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="41679281A0FFFEA4BBE52EF9687F1CB1" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">
<bibRefCitation id="E70D7283D9C8F26EF02044E4E5B941F3" author="Palm, T" journalOrPublisher="Entomologiska Foereningen i Stockholm, Stockholm" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" refId="B158" refString="Palm, T, 1961. Svensk Insektfauna 9. Skalbaggar, Coleoptera. Kortvingar: Fam. Staphylinidae, Haefte 2. Underfam. Oxytelinae, Oxyporinae, Steninae, Euaesthetinae. Entomologiska Foereningen i Stockholm, Stockholm" title="Svensk Insektfauna 9. Skalbaggar, Coleoptera. Kortvingar: Fam. Staphylinidae, Haefte 2. Underfam. Oxytelinae, Oxyporinae, Steninae, Euaesthetinae." year="1961">Palm (1961)</bibRefCitation>
(as synonym 
<taxonomicName id="34DF5FA98B0472CD6C7E1FC715AEBF41" genus="B." lsidName="B. fracticornis" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" rank="species" species="fracticornis">
<emphasis id="5ABC5C5ADA66D64A19A6DD6CC4876D7F" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">B. fracticornis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) states that this species can be found in half-moist sand, gravel, clay or mineral soil mixed with humus, with or without vegetation cover. In Central Europe, this species occurs on sandy to muddy river banks, and also in damp field edges (
<bibRefCitation id="7C5349F8DD886B8065104AAE769A7346" author="Schuelke, M" editor="Assing, V" journalOrPublisher="PhD Thesis, Michigan State University, Department of Entomology" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" refId="B185" refString="Schuelke, M, Assing, V, Schuelke, M, 2012a. Oxytelinae. In: AssingVSchuelkeM (Eds) Die Kaefer Mitteleuropas, Band 4 (2.Auflage). Spektrum Akademischer Verlag, Heidelberg, 283-284." title="Oxytelinae. In: AssingVSchuelkeM (Eds) Die Kaefer Mitteleuropas, Band 4 (2. Auflage). Spektrum Akademischer Verlag, Heidelberg, 283 - 284." year="2012 a">
<normalizedToken id="160388A76840DF76B77C1618F8863300" originalValue="Schülke">Schuelke</normalizedToken>
2012a
</bibRefCitation>
). Three of the CBG specimens were collected at a UV light at a forest edge, one was caught in a Malaise trap in a forested peninsula.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="0AE943E7CD14DBCCD357C0BB24CACCD5" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" type="comments">
<paragraph id="9D0E73B4379B166C7638569179749260" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D27860D40A2F834BEDE9B520C2FB3116" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">
<taxonomicName id="E32E091223D5438907919C49F3900E27" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Bledius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Bledius gallicus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gallicus">
<emphasis id="6D70D2D74B7F6505DA271FC1DFDC3403" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Bledius gallicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be recognized within 
<bibRefCitation id="C3787B3B2E4E736B5A32226C770EEB07" author="Herman, L" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" pagination="111 - 254" refId="B90" refString="Herman, L, 1972. Revision of Bledius and related genera. Part I. The aequatorialis, mandibularis, and semiferrugineus groups and two new genera (Coleopera, Staphylinidae, Oxytelinae). Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History 149: 111 - 254" title="Revision of Bledius and related genera. Part I. The aequatorialis, mandibularis, and semiferrugineus groups and two new genera (Coleopera, Staphylinidae, Oxytelinae)." volume="149" year="1972">
<normalizedToken id="459B16231F61A23E3912A8D7AA11601C" originalValue="Herman’s">Herman's</normalizedToken>
(1972)
</bibRefCitation>
'semiferrugineus 
<normalizedToken id="8BDACF3B023E3CAE6B13131F9B3BB278" originalValue="group’">group'</normalizedToken>
using the following combination of characters: last segment of metatarsus in dorsal view gradually expanded to apex, male sternite VII emarginate, with membranous lobe but emargination not bordered by a pair of spines, pronotum with midlongitudinal groove. The species will key easily to 
<taxonomicName id="0C9183EA390491F83188C035A15DFA9B" genus="B." lsidName="B. philadelphicus" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" rank="species" species="philadelphicus">
<emphasis id="979A1B5EC75A2F0D3C06A4B006661EA9" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">B. philadelphicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Fall, 1919 in 
<bibRefCitation id="BC32E20ABC2C013DA5E4F7198A25DD25" author="Herman, L" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" pagination="111 - 254" refId="B90" refString="Herman, L, 1972. Revision of Bledius and related genera. Part I. The aequatorialis, mandibularis, and semiferrugineus groups and two new genera (Coleopera, Staphylinidae, Oxytelinae). Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History 149: 111 - 254" title="Revision of Bledius and related genera. Part I. The aequatorialis, mandibularis, and semiferrugineus groups and two new genera (Coleopera, Staphylinidae, Oxytelinae)." volume="149" year="1972">
<normalizedToken id="E9636DACFD93E8173BF6152D982763E2" originalValue="Herman’s">Herman's</normalizedToken>
(1972)
</bibRefCitation>
key and we here consider these two species synonyms. Specimens in the CNC identified as 
<taxonomicName id="49E5B4A5E4293A400A7D159E6EF831CE" genus="B." lsidName="B. philadelphicus" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" rank="species" species="philadelphicus">
<emphasis id="556FA6C4F53CF5EE2C8451E28687EA9A" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">B. philadelphicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by Lee Herman and included in his revision of the ' 
<emphasis id="BB621093161A5DFFF7C841741D85D618" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">semiferrugineus</emphasis>
<normalizedToken id="4ACD4DAAA4D89331CE528AB07184EF0C" originalValue="group’">group'</normalizedToken>
(
<bibRefCitation id="5E5D0277A4F5EBBC1CAC9421E6F31D30" author="Herman, L" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" pagination="111 - 254" refId="B90" refString="Herman, L, 1972. Revision of Bledius and related genera. Part I. The aequatorialis, mandibularis, and semiferrugineus groups and two new genera (Coleopera, Staphylinidae, Oxytelinae). Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History 149: 111 - 254" title="Revision of Bledius and related genera. Part I. The aequatorialis, mandibularis, and semiferrugineus groups and two new genera (Coleopera, Staphylinidae, Oxytelinae)." volume="149" year="1972">Herman 1972</bibRefCitation>
) were dissected and revealed to be 
<taxonomicName id="D349D8583668D81BD6C8DB9675F59A41" genus="B." lsidName="B. gallicus" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" rank="species" species="gallicus">
<emphasis id="1EF15433B59AACD7B64CB8C681A3DCB2" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">B. gallicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The description of 
<taxonomicName id="72185CAD431143BB082DCBB4E56C9E20" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Bledius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Bledius philadelphicus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="philadelphicus">
<emphasis id="ED3714069880A1B1085220E59C9D641F" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Bledius philadelphicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in 
<bibRefCitation id="6B72CD6774049AA9CA07330E0DE50709" author="Herman, L" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" pagination="111 - 254" refId="B90" refString="Herman, L, 1972. Revision of Bledius and related genera. Part I. The aequatorialis, mandibularis, and semiferrugineus groups and two new genera (Coleopera, Staphylinidae, Oxytelinae). Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History 149: 111 - 254" title="Revision of Bledius and related genera. Part I. The aequatorialis, mandibularis, and semiferrugineus groups and two new genera (Coleopera, Staphylinidae, Oxytelinae)." volume="149" year="1972">Herman (1972)</bibRefCitation>
corresponds to that of 
<taxonomicName id="8D519BC876326D2CA18BE86610EB8A91" genus="B." lsidName="B. gallicus" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" rank="species" species="gallicus">
<emphasis id="74A170A9C599C27219EDAE0AB7EA9D3F" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">B. gallicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in 
<bibRefCitation id="C40C976C82F073D9C3D787E671FA8660" author="Schuelke, M" editor="Assing, V" journalOrPublisher="PhD Thesis, Michigan State University, Department of Entomology" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" refId="B185" refString="Schuelke, M, Assing, V, Schuelke, M, 2012a. Oxytelinae. In: AssingVSchuelkeM (Eds) Die Kaefer Mitteleuropas, Band 4 (2.Auflage). Spektrum Akademischer Verlag, Heidelberg, 283-284." title="Oxytelinae. In: AssingVSchuelkeM (Eds) Die Kaefer Mitteleuropas, Band 4 (2. Auflage). Spektrum Akademischer Verlag, Heidelberg, 283 - 284." year="2012 a">
<normalizedToken id="ED2EC89D93EFEE865A57E2A6C64D6904" originalValue="Schülke">Schuelke</normalizedToken>
(2012a)
</bibRefCitation>
, including the characteristic male sternite VII (though the membranous part is slightly deeper in both Nearctic and Palaearctic populations than indicated by the illustration). 
<taxonomicName id="BF90B0371175C55A5599B9D95E7EE20A" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Bledius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Bledius gallicus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gallicus">
<emphasis id="FBD98773ADA6B4386469360EBFA17A34" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Bledius gallicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is closely related to the Palaearctic 
<taxonomicName id="B4A125EF18ECB8C95CDAC32E94A5998F" genus="B." lsidName="B. femoralis" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" rank="species" species="femoralis">
<emphasis id="400BD684F267F965007965E33AC7BD83" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">B. femoralis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Gyllenhal, 1827) (
<bibRefCitation id="C14A91C40C712278B7FDE8574FC6118E" author="Schuelke, M" editor="Assing, V" journalOrPublisher="PhD Thesis, Michigan State University, Department of Entomology" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" refId="B185" refString="Schuelke, M, Assing, V, Schuelke, M, 2012a. Oxytelinae. In: AssingVSchuelkeM (Eds) Die Kaefer Mitteleuropas, Band 4 (2.Auflage). Spektrum Akademischer Verlag, Heidelberg, 283-284." title="Oxytelinae. In: AssingVSchuelkeM (Eds) Die Kaefer Mitteleuropas, Band 4 (2. Auflage). Spektrum Akademischer Verlag, Heidelberg, 283 - 284." year="2012 a">
<normalizedToken id="8B68C6F88D202D8256736A4D52937E13" originalValue="Schülke">Schuelke</normalizedToken>
2012a
</bibRefCitation>
). The two species have extremely similar aedeagi, differing only in the apex of the ventral lamella (
<figureCitation id="C225F30F5A9F1FA4B1C5193873BB1F5B" captionStart="Figures 9, 10" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figures 9, 10. 9 Bledius gallicus (Gravenhorst) 9 A habitus, black elytra, L. Borowiec 9 B habitus, red-brown elytra, L. Borowiec 9 C aedeagus, ventral view, VL = ventral lamella M. Schuelke 9 D male sternite VII 10 Carpelimus elongatulus (Erichson) 10 A habitus 10 B aedeagus, ventral view, H. Schillhammer. Scale bars: 1.0 mm (9 A, B; 10 A), 0.2 mm (9 C), 0.2 mm (9 D), 0.25 mm (10 B)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.894.37862.figures9-10" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/362142" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.894.37862.figures9-10">Fig. 9C</figureCitation>
) (acute in 
<taxonomicName id="FE4581F709FF72E91B241808B75FAE49" genus="B." lsidName="B. femoralis" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" rank="species" species="femoralis">
<emphasis id="60369B40294AD75CD70DFC1E14E4C913" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">B. femoralis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and broadly truncate in 
<taxonomicName id="2679E1FEA8193AAFE95DD53ED7232712" genus="B." lsidName="B. gallicus" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" rank="species" species="gallicus">
<emphasis id="9C8235268CEA696235AC0D1DB5A55751" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">B. gallicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). These two species are more easily separated by the shape of male sternite VII (
<bibRefCitation id="AFCDF42282FBF6BD8C86097FEE134B8E" author="Schuelke, M" editor="Assing, V" journalOrPublisher="PhD Thesis, Michigan State University, Department of Entomology" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" refId="B185" refString="Schuelke, M, Assing, V, Schuelke, M, 2012a. Oxytelinae. In: AssingVSchuelkeM (Eds) Die Kaefer Mitteleuropas, Band 4 (2.Auflage). Spektrum Akademischer Verlag, Heidelberg, 283-284." title="Oxytelinae. In: AssingVSchuelkeM (Eds) Die Kaefer Mitteleuropas, Band 4 (2. Auflage). Spektrum Akademischer Verlag, Heidelberg, 283 - 284." year="2012 a">
<normalizedToken id="A78A697784C2F98200961BB5F04E99EC" originalValue="Schülke">Schuelke</normalizedToken>
2012a
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="042D470163FF9E7F47BF28ED8BE4CAEC" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">
Based on the specimens available at the CNC and reported by 
<bibRefCitation id="97D1C568A9C6B4044548D973C47B0332" author="Herman, L" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" pagination="111 - 254" refId="B90" refString="Herman, L, 1972. Revision of Bledius and related genera. Part I. The aequatorialis, mandibularis, and semiferrugineus groups and two new genera (Coleopera, Staphylinidae, Oxytelinae). Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History 149: 111 - 254" title="Revision of Bledius and related genera. Part I. The aequatorialis, mandibularis, and semiferrugineus groups and two new genera (Coleopera, Staphylinidae, Oxytelinae)." volume="149" year="1972">Herman (1972)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<taxonomicName id="AD0D646034E98A82BD830657AB7F613B" genus="B." lsidName="B. gallicus" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" rank="species" species="gallicus">
<emphasis id="92556CFD5823D818CE4A65F54D79FD00" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">B. gallicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been in North America for quite a long time, since at least as early as 1910, when 
<bibRefCitation id="AF69EAA62159C1C743AE761687B1B0F9" author="Fall, HC" journalOrPublisher="Transactions of the American Entomological Society" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" pagination="89 - 197" refId="B59" refString="Fall, HC, 1910. Miscellaneous notes and descriptions of North American Coleoptera. Transactions of the American Entomological Society 36: 89 - 197" title="Miscellaneous notes and descriptions of North American Coleoptera." volume="36" year="1910">Fall (1910)</bibRefCitation>
first described 
<taxonomicName id="6E0BC2A81F08B8FE6A2BDF028F1AE321" genus="B." lsidName="B. philadelphicus" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" rank="species" species="philadelphicus">
<emphasis id="AD935DFF6E781DF40BB60F3AE9E52CE9" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">B. philadelphicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as 
<taxonomicName id="E5B4770B75F55236903D2A021920E9E0" genus="B." lsidName="B. dissimilis" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" rank="species" species="dissimilis">
<emphasis id="D0C30339C506CF051CB79599C5D0F8EC" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">B. dissimilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(not Erichson 1840, preoccupied name replaced by 
<bibRefCitation id="A0D0BF9D2BDD7FD9AF01F10CCB489AF9" author="Fall, HC" journalOrPublisher="Entomological News" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" pagination="1 - 26" refId="B60" refString="Fall, HC, 1919. A Change of Names (Coleoptera). Entomological News 30: 1 - 26" title="A Change of Names (Coleoptera)." volume="30" year="1919">Fall (1919)</bibRefCitation>
). The earliest Canadian specimens are from the 1920s.
</paragraph>
